Post_ID: 2761202702763851797 | Post_Code: CZRwzqLFoAV | Likes: 121 | Caption: Leave No Trace Principle 2: Travel and Camp on Durable Surfaces ⬇️<\br><\br>Continuing with our LNT series, let’s talk about principle 2!<\br><\br>Choosing durable surfaces to travel and camp on greatly impacts the degradation of the environment. <\br><\br>🥾RULE OF THUMB: stay on the provided trails. Trails are built to be able to limit the destruction of the nearby areas, to keep the traffic in a designated area. So, whenever possible, stay on the trail.<\br><\br>🥾BUT, LET’S BE REAL, there are times we have all gone off the trail! Whether you’re searching for a private “bathroom” area, taking a lunch break,  finding a campsite, or scrambling up some rock to get to a vista, it’s just part of hiking! <\br><\br>🪨 Because of this, it’s important to BE CONSCIOUS of where you travel off trail. Rocky areas are often able to withstand a lot more travel than vegetation and living soil. <\br><\br>👣 If you must travel through these areas, be conscious of your impact. (Sometimes this means spreading out from your group (vegetation), sometimes it means following exact footprints (soil))<\br><\br>🏕CAMPING on durable surfaces:<\br>Choose a campsite that either already has very high traffic (no vegetation left) or, in less trafficked areas, find locations you can have the least impact on. Generally, rock and sand are great areas to set up camp, as they will be able to withstand campers. <\br><\br>⛺️🥘CAMP COOKING: Set up camp kitchens on Rocky areas to avoid constant trampling on vegetation and soil. <\br><\br>This principle is EXTENSIVE and every situation differs. Your situation changes in different locations, the type of trip, and the local environment. We highly recommend you go check out lnt.org for more information on how to implement this principle, but we hope this gave you a good idea of the general guidelines!<\br><\br>Overall, it is our jobs to take into consideration the environment around us to decide how we can best limit our impact on each trip.<\br><\br>We also feel it’s important to recognize that while “stay on the trail” is a good rule of thumb, there are circumstances when you just CAN’T. Being able to know how to handle those moments and travel off trail responsibly is super important and can help us all to take better care of these lands! | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1643381034

Post_ID: 2760401047665658984 | Post_Code: CZO6iCrukxo | Likes: 158 | Caption: Want a simple way to help conserve the outdoors and pay it forward? Be Prepared for your outdoor experience. Being prepared lessens the strain on resources, especially in rural areas without a lot of resources. Post_ID: 2760078930242506807 | Post_Code: CZNxSndJRA3 | Likes: 106 | Caption: Before and after - this is what campsite restoration looks like! <\br><\br>Picture 1 shows an illegal campsite that had been heavily used, leaving the area without vegetation or healthy soil. Picture 2 shows the area after the soil has been decompacted to allow for aeration, moisture retention, and root growth. It was then covered in a layer of topsoil and dead vegetation. If left alone, this vegetation will start to decompose, adding necessary nutrients back into the soil and returning this patch to a healthy state. <\br><\br>Rangers and restoration crews work hard to return these areas to their natural state. If you see something that looks like picture 2, please leave it as is and find a more sustainable spot to stop!<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#restoration #rangers #jmt #johnmuirtrail #wildernessrestoration #sustainable #camping #natural #naturalization #leavenotrace #lnt | Tags: ['#restoration', '#rangers', '#jmt', '#johnmuirtrail', '#wildernessrestoration', '#sustainable', '#camping', '#natural', '#naturalization', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt'] | Time Stamp: 1643247070

Post_ID: 2759941819536871849 | Post_Code: CZNSHZKPZGp | Likes: 24 | Caption: Happy #WildernessWednesday! Today we're taking in the beauty found in the San Gorgonio Wilderness in Southern California! Nestled in San Bernardino National Forest, this designated wilderness also resides within the Sand to Snow National Monument. <\br>.<\br>The San Gorgonio Wilderness consists of sub-alpine landscape surrounded by desert to the east, and covers 94,000+ acres. With elevations from 4,400'-11,500', you can experience soft rolling foothills, to canyons, to steep, impressive mountains. Due to the elevation gradient, this wilderness has a transition between desert, coastal and mountain environments, including the different types of vegetation representative of each elevation.<\br>.<\br>The U.S. Congress designated the San Gorgonio Wilderness in 1964, making it one of the first designated wilderness areas in the U.S. The wilderness is named after San Gorgonio Mountain, which at 11,499 ft. is the highest peak in California south of the Sierra Nevada. San Gorgonio Mountain, however, was originally known as "Old Grayback" by locals until officially designated by the US Geological Survey in 1899.<\br>.<\br>There are 81 miles of trails in the National Forest section of the Wilderness, and ~20 miles of the Pacific Crest National Scenic Trail in the Bureau of Land Management portion. <\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#willdernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #wildernesswednesdays  #sangoroniowilderness #sangorgonio #sangorgoniopeak #sangorgoniopass #usfs #sanbernardinonationalforest #itsallyours #usforestservice #designatedwilderness #pacificcresttrail #pct #bureauoflandmanagement #blm #california #oldgraybackmountain #oldgrayback #optoutside #leavenotrace #lnt #photography #wilderness #camping #backpacking #colorpalette #colors #colorwheel | Tags: ['#WildernessWednesday', '#willdernessvolunteers', '#givingsomethingback', '#wildernesswednesdays', '#sangoroniowilderness', '#sangorgonio', '#sangorgoniopeak', '#sangorgoniopass', '#usfs', '#sanbernardinonationalforest', '#itsallyours', '#usforestservice', '#designatedwilderness', '#pacificcresttrail', '#pct', '#bureauoflandmanagement', '#blm', '#california', '#oldgraybackmountain', '#oldgrayback', '#optoutside', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#photography', '#wilderness', '#camping', '#backpacking', '#colorpalette', '#colors', '#colorwheel'] | Time Stamp: 1643230725
Post_ID: 2759927452602728610 | Post_Code: CZNO2U6PACi | Likes: 7 | Caption: YOU ARE WORTH IT<\br>Make investing in yourself your new habit. If you are not worth your own time and money, then what is? You wouldn't even be able to enjoy anything in life without being physically and mentally healthy in the first place. Then why not invest in the things that make you happy and healthy, every day? The same goes for relationships, we may put others' happiness and wellbeing before our own, but how can we help anyone if we are not feeling well? You can't save anybody from drowning if you are struggling yourself. In a plane accident, you gotta put on your own oxygen mask first. The thing is that investing in yourself IS scary, it takes courage to face the fear of failure in exploring your own darkness and pursuing your dreams. I know it well, I've been there, dazed and confused for a long time. Not that I got it all figured out nowadays, but after a lot of work on myself and years of study, I have the tools to navigate difficult situations (like moving overseas on my own while starting an online business after a burnout and a breakup 😂). Most importantly, I keep investing in myself EVERY SINGLE DAY. Through healthy habits, moving my body, fueling it with clean nutritious food, cultivating gratitude and positive thoughts, journalling, coaching, study, yoga and self-inquiry. I have spent thousands in this and dedicate many hours to it every day, because I love it so much that I have made it my job, but you don't have to take that long or spend that much. As little as 5 or 15 minutes, however much time you can find in your day, will have a ripple effect if you make it a habit. Your investment in yourself may be some daily stretching or workout, a walk outdoors or a dance in your kitchen, a morning gratitude list or an evening meditation. It may be quitting the job that you don't like, or asking for a promotion. It may be breaking the relationship where you are no longer happy, or going all in and commiting fully. It may be moving to the other side of the world, or buying a house in your hometown. It may be starting yoga, coaching, therapy, or a poney farm. Whatever it is, find what your heart desires and JUST DO IT. And let me know if I can help 😘 | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1643229012

Post_ID: 2759779508544354346 | Post_Code: CZMtNdRMDgq | Likes: 11 | Caption: Hoy en día, hay ciertos tratamientos o terapias como la cognitiva, que consisten en dar información al paciente sobre la situación que teme, para que confíe en el problema. Esto es muy habitual en personas que sufren, por ejemplo, aerofobia o miedo a volar.<\br><\br>No obstante, también hay alternativas a la medicina tradicional como son la&nbsp;sanación cuántica. Este método es novedoso y ofrece resultados excelentes. Pero ¿sabes cómo funciona? ¿O cuáles son las ventajas que ofrece al paciente?<\br><\br>Concretamente, la&nbsp;medicina cuántica&nbsp;se caracteriza por aplicar una serie de técnicas de sanación en las que hay una relación directa entre las emociones, los pensamientos y las células. Así lo sostienen el físico&nbsp;Amit Goswami&nbsp;y el biólogo&nbsp;Bruce Lipton.<\br><\br>Lo que se pretende es&nbsp;encontrar las debilidades&nbsp;que puedan generar el malestar físico o bloqueo emocional o cualquier cosa que impida un equilibrio personal. Una vez que se detecta se van a producir unos cambios energéticos y una mejoría de forma progresiva.<\br><\br>Este tipo de&nbsp;terapia sanadora&nbsp;utiliza los avances de la física cuántica con los conocimientos de la medicina tradicional china. El cuerpo es el reflejo de todo lo que acontece en nuestra vida y genera desequilibrios que afectan directamente a nuestra salud.<\br><\br>Los terapeutas irán grabando una nueva información en el&nbsp;cuerpo energético&nbsp;del paciente para eliminar poco a poco el problema que genera la fobia. En algunos casos, el resultado se logra en una sola sesión, mientras que, en otras ocasiones, se necesitan varias para percibir alguna mejoría.<\br><\br>#terapiacuantica #lnt #lntbarcelona #tierracrecimientopersonal #tierragururaskaur #sandragururaskaur #lntsantacoloma #santacoloma | Tags: ['#terapiacuantica', '#lnt', '#lntbarcelona', '#tierracrecimientopersonal', '#tierragururaskaur', '#sandragururaskaur', '#lntsantacoloma', '#santacoloma'] | Time Stamp: 1643211376

Post_ID: 2759266281629246075 | Post_Code: CZK4hBdOWJ7 | Likes: 48 | Caption: This is the sorghum mill at the Lyon Farm, one of the many agricultural outbuildings that dots the historic site (here, @flatrockarchives Co-Founder Johnny Waits leads a tour of the site to discuss its connection to the historic Flat Rock community). Sorghum syrup is similar to maple syrup or molasses, a sweet, sticky concoction derived form the sorghum plant. To make sorghum syrup, you crush the stalks of the sorghum plant, which produces a juice. The juice is then boiled, so that excess water evaporates as steam and only the sweet syrup remains.<\br>The Lyon family enslaved people prior to the Civil War, and continued to live on and farm the Lyon property until the early 2000's. This mill was used by later generations of the Lyon family as they worked on the farm. You can experience the full tour of the Flat Rock Archives by signing up for an @airbnb experience, where Johnny Waits leads you on a tour through Flat Rock's history, from enslavement to the present day.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT #history #blackhistory #sorghum | Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT', '#history', '#blackhistory', '#sorghum'] | Time Stamp: 1643150194

Post_ID: 2758599709314381047 | Post_Code: CZIg9HnLfT3 | Likes: 33 | Caption: I spent the weekend renewing my Wilderness First Responder certification with @nolsedu 💉🩸<\br><\br>And it reminded me how much can go WRONG, especially in remote environments 🤕 <\br><\br>What gives me confidence, though, is the fact that planning ahead and preparing really DOES help prevent accidents. <\br><\br>And an ounce of prevention IS worth a pound of cure… <\br><\br>Here are some ways you can avoid catastrophe on your next trip into the backcountry: <\br><\br>👉 bring a first aid kit! The size/contents of your kit can fluctuate based on how many people are in your group, where you are traveling (remoteness) and for how long, and the activities you’ll be doing<\br><\br>👉 have a plan incase of emergency; who will you contact for help? Know how to deliver a detailed patient report to EMS/SAR in the event you need an evacuation, and make sure you have an exit strategy, even if it is just marching back out the way you came <\br><\br>👉 seek out first aid training! A WFA is more affordable but less comprehensive than a WFR, and a WEMT is the most comprehensive wilderness medicine cert you can obtain (check out @nolsedu for more course info)<\br><\br>👉 lastly, know your limits. If you plan to go BIG, do so with the understanding that you might have to bail, and make sure you CAN bail, some routes are more committing than others. <\br><\br>Anytime we go out into the backcountry, we do so knowing that there is some risk involved. And when (if) we call for help, we are asking others to put their lives on the line for us. <\br><\br>Traveling safely and sustainably in the backcountry is an intentional practice 🌱<\br><\br>Photo of Jai carrying the @gossamergear Mariposa, 📸 taken by @mountainmagicmedia <\br><\br>#shetreks #wildernessmedicine #emergencypreparedness #backpacking #adventurecompany #womenwhobackpack #firstaid #planaheadandprepare #lnt #safetravels #nolswildernessmedicine #gossamergear | Tags: ['#shetreks', '#wildernessmedicine', '#emergencypreparedness', '#backpacking', '#adventurecompany', '#womenwhobackpack', '#firstaid', '#planaheadandprepare', '#lnt', '#safetravels', '#nolswildernessmedicine', '#gossamergear'] | Time Stamp: 1643070733

Post_ID: 2758374658856713948 | Post_Code: CZHtyNCl_7c | Likes: 14 | Caption: Bathroom facilities, such as pit toilets and outhouses, are preferred for all seasons. However, these options aren’t always available in the winter.<\br><\br>Cat holes are a common alternative, but they only work when the ground isn't frozen. In addition, when waste is buried in the snow, it cannot easily decompose. This may lead to wildlife finding your waste and unsanitary conditions when the snow melts in the spring, including polluted waters and the spread of fecal-born diseases.<\br><\br>Follow these tips for your next winter adventure:<\br>❄ To pee, make sure you are 70 big steps away from water, even if it is snow covered.<\br>❄ To poop, be prepared to pack it out using a WAG bag.<\br>❄ Always pack out toilet paper and hygiene products.<\br><\br>When you know what to do when you GottaGo!, doing what's natural 💩, becomes second nature. 😜 Find more info at GottaGoUtah.org.<\br><\br>#winterrecreation #GottaGo #GoBeforeYouGo #naturecalls #everyonepoops #outdoorrecreation #leavenotrace #LNT #leaveitbetterthanyoufoundit #packitinpackitout #dontbetrashy #packitout #naturefirst #publiclands #utahlife #beutahful #igutah | Tags: ['#winterrecreation', '#GottaGo', '#GoBeforeYouGo', '#naturecalls', '#everyonepoops', '#outdoorrecreation', '#leavenotrace', '#LNT', '#leaveitbetterthanyoufoundit', '#packitinpackitout', '#dontbetrashy', '#packitout', '#naturefirst', '#publiclands', '#utahlife', '#beutahful', '#igutah'] | Time Stamp: 1643043905

Post_ID: 2757670839085689994 | Post_Code: CZFNwRzJ-yK | Likes: 17 | Caption: ADICCIONES<\br><\br>Muchas personas buscan llenar sus vacíos con cosas externas. <\br><\br>Las adicciones a sustancias como en el caso de  adicciones conductuales están asociadas a emociones, sensaciones y sentimientos. <\br><\br>Comprender el significado emocional de las adicciones permite abordar cambios en uno mismo y en cómo se relaciona con otros y con el entorno para poder dejar atrás la adicción. <\br><\br>El miedo, la falta de autoestima, la soledad, la inmadurez emocional, la inseguridad, las ganas de huir de las responsabilidades o de la realidad de la vida propia, son solo algunas de las motivaciones detrás de las adicciones. <\br><\br>Es el vacío existencial de la mayoría de las personas lo que las motiva a buscar estos escapes, que más que soluciones, solo ofrecen un momento de placer, pero no de crecimiento, avance o resolución.<\br><\br>La falta de autoconocimiento lo que hace que la humanidad se pierda en todo lo externo y busque esas experiencias para “sentir” algo especial en su vida.<\br><\br>Tapar vacíos solo nos hace que éste se incremente.<\br><\br>Cuanto más vacía está la vida, más pesada es. Post_ID: 2757556819901863629 | Post_Code: CZEz1FKNNbN | Likes: 113 | Caption: An easy habit to take up this year is to Leave No Trace whenever you’re out in nature. Follow this list of principles to ensure the safety and enjoyment of the outdoors by all visitors and protect natural landscapes.<\br> <\br>🗺Plan and prepare- Plan the routes to take and the abilities of your group. Choose appropriate clothing for the activity you plan to do and the weather for the day.<\br> <\br>🥾Traveling on Durable Surfaces means walking on surfaces that won’t harm plant life. Rock, gravel, and sand are all surfaces that can withstand repeated foot traffic.<\br> <\br>🚯Dispose of Waste Properly- As stewards of the Earth, it is our responsibility to take care of it. Carry trash and food scraps out and properly dispose of them to keep Olana’s wildlife healthy.<\br> <\br>🌲Leave What You Find- Rocks are fun, sticks are cool, and berries are yummy, but nature needs all of it to keep ecosystems intact. <\br> <\br>Grace King said in July of 1891<\br>“Not a daisy is allowed to be pulled, not a cat’s tail – and as for goldenrod!  The other day we drove miles to get some yellow daisies & sweet fern, when there were prairies of it all round about here – but that would have despoiled the place – taken a little from its beauty.”<\br> <\br>🔥Minimize Campfire Impacts- Campfires and smoking are not allowed at Olana, but it’s great advice for outings in other areas. Upstate New York experiences wildfires so keep an eye on, minor sources of heat.<\br> <\br>🐾Respect Wildlife- Wild animals that inhabit Olana are majestic, so let’s keep them that way. Observe from a distance and let them be. Animals need space to live healthy lives. Don’t try to feed them, call to them, touch them, or pick them up.<\br> <\br>🌟Be Considerate of Others- People go outdoors to enjoy the sounds and sights of nature. Enhance this experience for everyone by keeping group sizes small, voices soft, leashing and cleaning up after dogs, and letting uphill walkers pass first on narrow trails.<\br> <\br>#lnt @leavenotraceorg  #nature #outdoors #landscape #wildlife #respectnature #outdoors #nystateparks #olana #olanashs #olanastatehistoricsite #theolanapartnership #hudson #hvny @catskillcenter #catskills #hudsonriver @nystateparks | Tags: ['#lnt', '#nature', '#outdoors', '#landscape', '#wildlife', '#respectnature', '#outdoors', '#nystateparks', '#olana', '#olanashs', '#olanastatehistoricsite', '#theolanapartnership', '#hudson', '#hvny', '#catskills', '#hudsonriver'] | Time Stamp: 1642946411

Post_ID: 2756446639363583806 | Post_Code: CZA3Z09le8- | Likes: 9 | Caption: Day 100 (Sat 7/24); Lander, Wyoming<\br><\br>This morning after we packed up and were in the process of heading to breakfast, we learned from someone we were passing that there was a farmers market in the park. So we decided to stay there and get breakfast from the local vendors, and we also learned that an art festival was happening concurrently in the park. We hung out for the beginning of the art fair and watched the local fire department child drum and bagpipe corp perform. We then left to get more caffeine, meet up with Nude Beach who stayed in a hotel, check out the gear store, and hangout out the library to charge up our batteries. The librarians remembered us from yesterday and our glowing review of the library. They took our pictures and asked us to write something because apparently the library is regularly on the chopping block when it comes to city budget. Bison asks to play the piano in the little theatre room we saw, and they ended up taking us to the original library building, which was a Carnegie Library (look it up) that has a baby grand piano. We play piano, sing, charge, and download for a few hours before we head out for a late lunch. We then went back to the pool for another soak before resupplying, where we run into Nibbles and Threshold! We pick up Dominos pizza, head back to the park to celebrate Christmas in July by watching Christmas television episodes, then sleep in the dugout again. Post_ID: 2756350159280677101 | Post_Code: CZAhd24hCDt | Likes: 71 | Caption: #제품협찬<\br><\br>대체육은 콩으로 식물성 고기를 만드는게 일반적인데 위미트 비건 프라이드는 버섯이 주재료라고 해요. 비주얼적으로나 맛으로나 일반 치킨과 거의 흡사해서 놀랐고 맛은 또 부드러워서 좋았어요. 요즘 채식 제품이 갈수록 다양해지고 관심도 높아진 것 같아요. <\br><\br>그냥 굽거나 튀겨도 맛있지만 저는 치킨탕수를 만들어 보았어요. 탕수육 소스 만드는게 비교적 쉬운 편이라 활용해보았는데 맛있더라고요. 개인적으로 단 것을 좋아하지 않아 청양 소스를 찍어먹었는데 생각했던 것보다 맵지 않아서 아쉬웠어요. 그래도 단맛을 중화해주어 나쁘진 않은 편이었어요. <\br><\br>채식을 시작할 땐 마냥 어렵게 느껴지던 레시피들이 나만의 방식으로 요리를 하면서 점차 그 범위가 무궁무진함을 느꼈어요. 조미료에서 가끔 브레이크가 걸리기는 하지만 그렇게까지 완벽하게 채식을 이어갈 필요는 없다고 생각해요. 그래서 전 여전히 하루 한끼, 일주일에 며칠이라도 꼭 채식 식단을 짜며 가족들의 건강과 환경을 책임지고 있답니다. <\br><\br>@vegeharu_official <\br>@clean_hikers <\br>@eat_wemeet <\br><\br>#채식하루 #위미트 #vegan #비건치킨 #나의비거니즘일기 #위미트비건프라이드 #쿠킹챌린지 #치킨탕수 | Tags: ['#제품협찬', '#채식하루', '#위미트', '#vegan', '#비건치킨', '#나의비거니즘일기', '#위미트비건프라이드', '#쿠킹챌린지', '#치킨탕수'] | Time Stamp: 1642802565
Post_ID: 2756345028726336707 | Post_Code: CZAgTMrpazD | Likes: 6 | Caption: HIPERACTIVIDAD <\br><\br>El trastorno de déficit de atención con hiperactividad, también conocido como TDAH, es una afección psicológica que afecta tanto a niños como a adultos. Sus síntomas son:<\br><\br>→ Inquietud, impulsividad<\br><\br>→ Falta de concentración y atención<\br><\br>→Tienden a cometer errores en el colegio o en el trabajo <\br><\br>→ Tratan de evitar realizar actividades o tareas que requieran de una atención sostenida en el tiempo<\br><\br>→ No consiguen seguir las instrucciones que se les aporta en la escuela o trabajo<\br><\br>→ Dificultad para esperar su turno o esperar a que la otra persona termine de hablar <\br><\br>→ Impulso de levantarse, moverse, correr y deambular<\br><\br>Con TERAPIA ENERGÉTICA se trabajan los 3 cuerpos: el físico, el energético/emocional y el espiritual.<\br><\br>Es un método alternativo para acceder al origen. Here's 5 easy tips to have a responsible visit to Arches National Park:<\br><\br>-Timed Entry reservation is required <\br>From April 3 to October 3, 2022 Arches will implement a temporary, pilot timed entry system to help manage traffic and improve visitor experiences.Visit nps.gov/arch for more info<\br><\br>-No drones allowed (as in any national park)<\br>It is always unlawful to launch, fly and land a drone inside National Parks<\br><\br>-Watch your step for delicate cryptobiotic soil<\br>Arches is home to a unique living soil crust. “Once damaged, crusts may take many years to grow back. Areas that have been stripped of crusts are vulnerable to erosion, flooding, dust storms, loss of organic materials, and invasion by non-native weeds that thrive on disturbed soil.”-NPS<\br><\br>-”Light Painting” photography is prohibited in the park.<\br>“Note that using artificial light sources to light up landscapes, rock formations, or other park features is prohibited. - NPS<\br><\br>-Always stay hydrated and be prepared for varying temps.<\br>Hydration is a key factor for any adventure. Post_ID: 2755515710706169847 | Post_Code: CY9jvCFpjf3 | Likes: 22 | Caption: Day 99 (Fri 7/23) 3 Trail Miles & A Hitch into Lander<\br><\br>We woke up this morning and packed up immediately without breakfast because we only had about an hour of hiking before we'd get to the road. I'm in a much better mood knowing that we're out of the Basin and about to relax in town with some hikers who are ahead of us. We throw out the thumb and get picked up by an RV covered in cartoon characters and with three cats inside. It's piloted by a nice retired couple who let their grandchildren paint the outside. They drop us off at the post office, we grab our packages with our bear gear (we're heading into grizzly territory!), and then get McDonald's. We then go into tow and, hit up the library to upload podcast recordings. We check out the church where there is supposedly going to be a community potluck later, go eat some very tasty ice cream, and then head to the local high school where the pool is open for public use. We make use of the showers, and it turns out there's a hot tub at this high school??? We soak in it for a while and make conversation with Jenn, who's there with her kids. Jenn gives us a lift to the laundromat, pays for our laundry, and even offers us dinner and her trampoline to sleep on! Jenn's the best! Nude Beach shows up while we're doing laundry, and afterwards we hangout at Gannet Grill & Bar with other hikers in town. We make a (slightly buzzed) walk to the park where they let people camp. It's dark and we're not quite sure where the camping is, so we end up sleeping in the dugout of the baseball fields (we learned our lesson from the sprinklers in Creede).<\br><\br>#newmexico #colorado #wyoming #idaho #montana #embracethebrutality #thetrek #hikingaddict #gooutside #staywild #hikertrash #continentaldividetrail #cdt2021 #mexicotocanada #backpacking #thruhike  #optoutside #camping #longdistancehiking #outdoors #choosemountains #LNT #leavenotrace #camp #summercamp #funnestknowntime | Tags: ['#newmexico', '#colorado', '#wyoming', '#idaho', '#montana', '#embracethebrutality', '#thetrek', '#hikingaddict', '#gooutside', '#staywild', '#hikertrash', '#continentaldividetrail', '#cdt2021', '#mexicotocanada', '#backpacking', '#thruhike', '#optoutside', '#camping', '#longdistancehiking', '#outdoors', '#choosemountains', '#LNT', '#leavenotrace', '#camp', '#summercamp', '#funnestknowntime'] | Time Stamp: 1642703091
Post_ID: 2755512673486295373 | Post_Code: CY9jC1dPNFN | Likes: 47 | Caption: Should you build a fire?<\br>The most important consideration to be made when deciding to use a fire is the potential damage to the backcountry.<\br>What is the fire danger for the time of year and the location you have selected? n Are there administrative restrictions from the agency that administers the area?<\br>Is there sufficient wood so its removal will not be noticeable?<\br>Does the harshness of alpine and desert growing conditions for trees and shrubs mean that the regeneration of wood sources cannot keep pace with the demand for firewood?<\br>Do group members possess the skill to build a campfire that will Leave No Trace?<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br> #leavenotrace #lnt #nature #naturephotography #getoutinthewoods #outdoorlifetgroughmylens #forest #forestview #mountainviewpnw #hike #hiking #hikingparadise #hikingbangers #bootsonthetrail #hikingadventures #hikingtheworld #coastalhikingtrail #trailview #britishcolumbianature #britishcolumbia #VancouverIsland #vancouverislandhiking #westcoastwonderland #explorevi #explorenanaimo #centralvancouverisland #VancouverIslandtrails #valhallakingdom #woodsexplorer<\br>#leavenotracethursday via @preview.app | Tags: ['#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#nature', '#naturephotography', '#getoutinthewoods', '#outdoorlifetgroughmylens', '#forest', '#forestview', '#mountainviewpnw', '#hike', '#hiking', '#hikingparadise', '#hikingbangers', '#bootsonthetrail', '#hikingadventures', '#hikingtheworld', '#coastalhikingtrail', '#trailview', '#britishcolumbianature', '#britishcolumbia', '#VancouverIsland', '#vancouverislandhiking', '#westcoastwonderland', '#explorevi', '#explorenanaimo', '#centralvancouverisland', '#VancouverIslandtrails', '#valhallakingdom', '#woodsexplorer', '#leavenotracethursday'] | Time Stamp: 1642702729

Post_ID: 2754727615202270259 | Post_Code: CY6wiu9Fxwz | Likes: 20 | Caption: Day 98 (Thu 7/22): 30ish miles<\br><\br>We wake up in the morning to find Bison camped next to us. We eat breakfast and pack up while he tells us about how he accidentally went 8-10 miles off trail yesterday. We then hike out. It's another long day of desert hiking, but we are actually on roads for a decent amount of it. I'm very fed up with the Basin at this point and am wishing any car would stop for a little bit of trail magic. We also start passing a bunch of posts for the Oregon Trail? And the California Trail, whatever that is? Near the end of the day I get to the water source I was planning on stopping at, but unfortunately it's a terrible spot. The next one is only a mile, so I suck it up and hike for another 20ish minutes. I am so glad I decided to go an extra mile because I arrive in South Pass City, a historical mining town, that now operates as a sort of museum/recreation area (Conner Prairie on a way smaller scale, for those from Fishers). There's a bathroom, piped water, and a spot where they let backpackers set up. I roll in at dusk, set up to cowboy camp and hang out with a with a guy cycling the Divide. Bison shows up, and later Nude Beach does as well. Bison warns me that it's probably going to rain and offers to let me sleep under his tarp so I don't have to set up my tent. I agree and help him set it up, which was a good call because it definitely stormed. Post_ID: 2754177820993583674 | Post_Code: CY4ziLMlPo6 | Likes: 455 | Caption: CONTRAST<\br>•<\br>It’s so hard to explain what a thru-hike feels like - I struggle to find the words to make sense of this experience. Us hiker trash usually end up nodding, not needing words, knowing together this secret world.<\br>•<\br>Rad and I pushed a single-day Presidential traverse. It was miserably wet, cold, and quiet. Besides the roar of raindrops and swirling wind, it was silent on the mountain.<\br>•<\br>I had become accustomed to clouds consuming the White Mountain vistas after that week. We imagined their glory but witnessed only clouds and trees. We had no energy to talk above the wind and we dragged our pruned feet over the wet rocks. <\br>•<\br>Later, while hiking up Mt. Lafayette, we realized we were no longer shrouded in clouds. We could see more than 100 feet ahead for the first time in New Hampshire!<\br>•<\br>I about cried with relief, and all I mustered was, “I didn’t realize how miserable I’ve been.”<\br>•<\br>Soon, we were buzzing with joy, vibrating and running laps around each other, taking photos and whooping excitedly. My soul warmed. We ran up to the summit to peer down on Franconia Ridge - one of the most famous views along the AT. Drifting clouds rolled over the ridge, cloaking the view and revealing it again. The fog danced and wrapped itself around ledges and little towers. Tiny people way way off in the distance disappeared into momentary voids.<\br>•<\br>One can become more grateful for five minutes of sunshine after a week rain than was ever before imaginable. I can’t put emotion into this; it’s impossible. If you know it, you know it. If you don't know yet, go find it, way out there.<\br>•<\br>#thruhike #appalachiantrail #thruhiker #hikertrash #atsobo2021 #southbound #thruhiking #ultralightbackpacking #longdistancehiking #franconiaridge #hikenewhampshire #whitemountains #alpinehiking #backpacking #sleepinthedirt #giveashit #leavenotrace #lnt | Tags: ['#thruhike', '#appalachiantrail', '#thruhiker', '#hikertrash', '#atsobo2021', '#southbound', '#thruhiking', '#ultralightbackpacking', '#longdistancehiking', '#franconiaridge', '#hikenewhampshire', '#whitemountains', '#alpinehiking', '#backpacking', '#sleepinthedirt', '#giveashit', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt'] | Time Stamp: 1642543603

Post_ID: 2754126812384548008 | Post_Code: CY4n75uj1So | Likes: 914 | Caption: Planning winter action? Don’t forget your traction! When it comes to trekking winter trails, traction devices are a must to help keep you on your feet:<\br>👍 Snowshoes are large frames that attach to your boots and prevent you from sinking deep into snow by distributing your weight over a greater surface area. Snowshoes also prevent postholing (when bare boots make deep holes in the snow), which can be hazardous for you and other visitors. Snowshoes should be worn wherever there is significant snowpack, and they are required in the Adirondack High Peaks Wilderness once snow depths reach 8 or more inches.<\br>👍 Hiking spikes pull on over your boots and are simple to put on/take off, making them easy to pack. Spike versions are best for flatter backwoods outings because they grip icy trails but can be worn down when used on hard surfaces like sidewalks or roads. Versions that use coils or studs aren’t secure on ice but can help with traction in light snow or on maintained trails.<\br>👍 Crampons are larger, sharper spikes on frames that attach to your boots. They penetrate ice, making them the best choice for thick ice and steep slopes.<\br><\br>No matter which is best for your adventure, remember to practice putting on and using your gear in a safe and familiar environment first. Picking the right footwear is just one part of planning ahead and preparing for a safe and enjoyable time outside. <\br><\br>(Pictured, in order: snowshoes, hiking spikes/microspikes, crampons) | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1642537522

Post_ID: 2754091438111708686 | Post_Code: CY4f5I3l9YO | Likes: 18 | Caption: Winter is a great time to get outdoors, but it can pose extra challenges when you gotta go. Most bathrooms are closed in the winter, and the waste disposal methods you usually use may not be possible.<\br><\br>Have you ever tried digging a cat hole through several feet of snow or in the frozen ground? Yeah, that likely didn't go so well. Don't worry, we've got some winter tips for you!<\br><\br>Follow these tips for your next winter adventure: <\br>❄️ To pee, make sure you are 70 big steps away from water, even if it is snow covered. <\br>❄️ To poop, be prepared to pack it out using a WAG bag. <\br>❄️ Always pack out toilet paper and hygiene products.<\br><\br>When you know what to do when you gotta go, doing what's natural 💩, becomes second nature. 😜<\br><\br>#winterwonderland #winterrecreation #GottaGo #GoBeforeYouGo #naturecalls #everyonepoops #outdoorrecreation #leavenotrace #LNT #leaveitbetterthanyoufoundit #packitinpackitout #dontbetrashy #packitout #naturefirst #publiclands #utahlife #beutahful #igutah | Tags: ['#winterwonderland', '#winterrecreation', '#GottaGo', '#GoBeforeYouGo', '#naturecalls', '#everyonepoops', '#outdoorrecreation', '#leavenotrace', '#LNT', '#leaveitbetterthanyoufoundit', '#packitinpackitout', '#dontbetrashy', '#packitout', '#naturefirst', '#publiclands', '#utahlife', '#beutahful', '#igutah'] | Time Stamp: 1642533305

Post_ID: 2753340860901124913 | Post_Code: CY11OzXlGsx | Likes: 19 | Caption: Day 96 (Tue 7/20) 30ish miles<\br><\br>Whenever we end up sleeping in a group of people, we get a reminder that everyone else starts way earlier than we do. Regardless, we packed up and hiked out. It's a long day of desert hiking, which is beautiful in how far you can see, but also is not the most visually dynamic. There's a reservoir that everyone on Guthook says you have to go to to cool off. We get there around noon, but somehow it also manages to be overcast the one day in the desert we're at a water source that hasn't been ruined by cows. Still we hang out regardless even if it isn't quite the oasis it would have been had the weather been hotter. I also finally see some of the wild horses of the basin! We hike until dusk intending to stop at the next water source, but I run into Nude Beach about three miles before the water, and we both decide to stop because we found the single patch of ground not covered in sagebrush and we didn't really want to hike for another hour. Post_ID: 2752886837469856161 | Post_Code: CY0N_5GPUGh | Likes: 168 | Caption: ｜到此一遊文化何時能消失？<\br><\br>所謂的無痕山林，指的不僅是不要留下垃圾，而是要盡可能地保護自然，維持自然原始的模樣，避免遭到人為破壞。<\br><\br>在台灣，許多地方可見遊客刻字、寫下某某某到此一遊的字樣，此舉不僅嚴重破壞自然環境，更讓美景失去原有光采。不過，這樣的行為可不是只有台灣人獨有。<\br><\br>在美國德州大彎國家公園 (Big Bend National Park)，管理當局在聖誕假期結束後，赫然發現園區內的數千年石版畫遭到遊客任意雕刻名字，被嚴重破壞。這些石塊是5000年到8500年前，當地原住民的創作，雖然版畫已不可見，但巨大的石塊錯落於國家公園內，是珍貴的歷史遺跡。<\br><\br>然而，竟然有遊客在12/26（之所以知道確切時間是因為遊客還押上日期），於石板上刻下自己的名字以及日期，白色的刻痕深深烙印在石板上，造成難以抹滅的痕跡。<\br><\br>後來有其他遊客看到，試圖要清除刻痕，於是使用自來水清洗，沒想到留下巨大白色痕跡。<\br><\br>大彎國家公園表示，這是自2015年來第50次有人破壞園區內的岩畫，去年，還有人在岩石上留下「白人力量」(White Power) 字樣，讓當局非常氣憤又難過。<\br><\br>這些刻痕，專家必須小心翼翼地使用蒸餾水搭配刷子，手動清除。對遊客來說，刻下一段話只需要幾秒鐘時間，然而要清除可能得花上數日甚至數周，且有些傷害難以扭轉，人為的破壞將永遠清晰可見。<\br><\br>這樣的情景，是否也會讓你想到台灣的許多名勝景點呢？<\br><\br>-<\br><\br>#bigbend #nationalpark #lnt #leavenotrace #outdoor #outdoorlife #outside #outsidermag #戶外即生活 #戶外生活 #戶外風格 #戶外人的風格事 #無痕山林 #環境保護 #大自然 | Tags: ['#bigbend', '#nationalpark', '#lnt', '#leavenotrace', '#outdoor', '#outdoorlife', '#outside', '#outsidermag', '#戶外即生活', '#戶外生活', '#戶外風格', '#戶外人的風格事', '#無痕山林', '#環境保護', '#大自然'] | Time Stamp: 1642389705

Post_ID: 2732341312255098420 | Post_Code: CXrOfJqFv40 | Likes: 26 | Caption: Day 75 (Tue 6/29): ??? miles<\br><\br>So after a rough night (no water, mildly heavy winds) I wake up and find that Nude Beach arrived later, that we passed Bison in the dark, and that we weren't too far from each other. No PDF, though. So I pack up and we start a steep, dangerous descent. There's no visible trail and it's all scree (small rocks that basically act as marbles when hiking). I'm very happy I didn't try to do this at night. I fall on my butt a few times, and after finally reaching the bottom and getting to water I find that both my water bottles had fallen out. Bison gave me one of his to use until we get to town. After regrouping with Nude Beach we have a meal break before starting a wild climb up and through the Argentine Ridge. This is the knifiest ridge ever, and as we get close to Gray's Peak (the highest point on trail) we are enveloped by clouds again. We get a message from PDF, who took a low route last evening and stopped just short of where we had planned to stop (but didn't make it to). He then got up early thinking we were ahead and was up and over Gray's Peak already. So we're feeling better about that, and we're feeling worse as we ascend the mountain because we hear thunder near the top. The worst place you can be when there may be lightning. We lose each other because of the clouds, but I run up to the top, snap a selfie (which I don't show now because it looks the same as my photo from yesterday), and start descending immediately. Luckily the other side is a well maintained trail and is easy to move quickly on. Once I clear the weather and feel safer, I start to run because I'm hungry and know at the end of this long dirt road is Bison's mom and aunt who will take us for food. We get picked up and find that his family made t-shirts from us! We go for dinner, grab Epson salts and breakfast foods, then back to the hotel.<\br><\br>Albums: Bacchanal 'N' Philadelphia by Mischief Brew. Approaching Thunder by We The Heathens. Post_ID: 2752060757551112779 | Post_Code: CYxSK2OIGJL | Likes: 2417 | Caption: Looking to leave a lighter footprint on the earth this year?<\br> <\br>A great resolution for nature lovers to help protect your National Parks can be to practice Leave No Trace principles all year round.<\br> <\br>The principles of Leave No Trace are low impact practices for anyone visiting the outdoors. Although Leave No Trace has its roots in backcountry settings, the actions can be applied anywhere — from remote wilderness areas, to local parks and even in your own backyard.<\br> <\br>Follow these seven points to minimize your impact on the outdoors: <\br>•	Plan ahead and prepare <\br>•	Travel and camp on durable surfaces <\br>•	Dispose of waste properly <\br>•	Leave what you find <\br>•	Minimize campfire impacts <\br>•	Respect wildlife <\br>•	Be considerate of other visitors <\br><\br>Share your best Leave No Trace tips in the comments.<\br><\br>Happy adventuring! <\br><\br>Photo/Emily Isabelle <\br>Image: View of craggy cliffside shoreline on Anacapa Island<\br><\br>#LNT#KnowBeforeYouGo | Tags: ['#LNT', '#KnowBeforeYouGo'] | Time Stamp: 1642291234

Post_ID: 2750386598719689827 | Post_Code: CYrVgoTrpRj | Likes: 41 | Caption: ALIGNMENT<\br>In the dictionary, alignment has to do with arranging on a straight line or correct position, which may or not be synonymous (luckily, life's hardly ever about straight lines, as much as we would like it to be sometimes). In yoga, we care, and sometimes even obsess 😂 over alignment for our poses: take the one pictured here, pincha mayurasana. The first pic is from a few months ago in Italy. I was helped to get up there, but once I could stack my hips over my shoulders in a (more or less) straight line, the position would almost hold itself. So the picture gives the illusion of stability, but I needed help to align myself. Fast-forward to today in my Brazilian living room: I still struggle with this on my mat almost every day, so I use a 3-step progression with the help of a block to align the hips on top of the shoulders. Firstly I put my head on a block (wonderful @mfmarquezd trick 😍), then I let the block sit between my hands with free head, finally I do without block. It's harder without because my hips are not as aligned on top of my shoulders when I kick up, mainly due to me being afraid of being upside down without any support. The lesson here is: IT'S THE SAME WITH LIFE. Once you are aligned, with your purpose, your routines, your surroundings, everything flows easily. But when you are not, Oh my is it a struggle. I have discovered that a little help from a pair of eyes outside the situation goes a long way to bring us into alignment and get over the fear. A little support, a little push even. I used to try to power through life's struggles (with so much unnecessary drama), but yoga has taught me the importance of alignment, to give up the drama and go with the flow. I have learnt to use the flow to carry me where I wanna go, with fiery determination but also compassionate patience. I have also learnt the importance of letting myself be helped: by my yoga teachers, by other healers and experts, by my own coach. With these posts, I hope to inspire you, like I was by many social media accounts during the pandemic. And maybe I can help you with alignment in yoga or in life, too. Post_ID: 2749875018094563670 | Post_Code: CYphMJuP1FW | Likes: 45 | Caption: It's #WildernessWednesday and today we're sharing photos from the Ansel Adams Wilderness areas in the Sierra National Forest. Tucked in the dramatic granite landscape of the Sierra Nevada mountain range, the Ansel Adams Wilderness encompasses 232,000 spectacular acres of granite peaks, steep-walled gorges, and rock outcroppings. <\br>.<\br>Several small glaciers cling to north and northeast facing slopes of the highest peaks. There are also a number of fairly large lakes on the eastern slope of the precipitous Ritter Range. Elevations range from 3,500 feet to 13,157 feet. The area includes approximately 350 miles of trails, including portions of the John Muir and Pacific Crest Trails. <\br>.<\br>79,000 acres of the Ansel Adams Wilderness are managed by the Inyo National Forest, while the remainder is managed by the Sierra National Forest and Devil’s Postpile National Monument. Ansel Adams Wilderness offers some beautiful views, outdoor enrichment, and some opportunities for solitude. We highly suggest you plan ahead and check it out!<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#willdernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #wildernesswednesdays #stewardship #conservation #anseladamswilderness #anseladams # #usfs #monocreektrail #sierranationalforest #itsallyours #usforestservice #designatedwilderness #california #sierranevadas #pacificcresttrail #optoutside #johnmuirtrail #leavenotrace #lnt #photography #wilderness #camping #backpacking #colorswatch #colorpalette #colors #colorwheel | Tags: ['#WildernessWednesday', '#willdernessvolunteers', '#givingsomethingback', '#wildernesswednesdays', '#stewardship', '#conservation', '#anseladamswilderness', '#anseladams', '#usfs', '#monocreektrail', '#sierranationalforest', '#itsallyours', '#usforestservice', '#designatedwilderness', '#california', '#sierranevadas', '#pacificcresttrail', '#optoutside', '#johnmuirtrail', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#photography', '#wilderness', '#camping', '#backpacking', '#colorswatch', '#colorpalette', '#colors', '#colorwheel'] | Time Stamp: 1642030668

Post_ID: 2749867433794731628 | Post_Code: CYpfdySv_5s | Likes: 456 | Caption: The future of our 🌎 depends on us! ⁠<\br>⁠<\br>With all of the overwhelming problems happening in the world right now (global warming, climate change, pollution), the reality can be sobering, discouraging, and well...kind of grim! We know how you feel...⁠<\br>⁠<\br>But what if there actually is something that YOU can do about it? Yes it's true! You can help and do something positive for our planet by being a Wild Keeper! 🥰⁠<\br>⁠<\br>What is a Wild Keeper you might ask? Wild Keepers are a community of nature lovers that care about our environment. Wild Keepers are on a mission to pick up trash outside, make a positive impact in the outdoor spaces that we enjoy, and have fun doing it as a part of a larger community of Wild Keepers while inspiring others to do the same! 🙌🌵🌲🥾⁠<\br>⁠<\br>Apply to be a Wild Keeper on January 27th, and do something good for our planet in 2022! Let's give back to this beautiful place we call home and make our future look a little brighter (and trash free)! Post_ID: 2749802954775836397 | Post_Code: CYpQzfhu7bt | Likes: 70 | Caption: This is a solution pit, a depression in the surface of the rock outcrops. You’ll find them anywhere there are rock outcrops in the National Heritage Area, especially in Davidson-Arabia Mountain Nature Preserve (@arabiaranger) and Panola Mountain State Park (@panolamountainstatepark). Solution pits take thousands of years to form in the rock face, a process that begins with two things: lichen and water. Water, as it falls on the outcrops, slowly erodes the granite. Meanwhile, lichen grows on the bare rock surface and releases a weak acid that reacts with the stone to, over time, further erode and indent the rock. These processes take place in geologic time, meaning that everything is very slow: thousands of years pass before a solution put looks like the ones you see today.<\br>As you hike, take care of the solution pits and stick to the bare granite. Remember, water on the outcrops is ephemeral, and solution pits sometimes are just filled with dry, sandy soil. By sticking to bare stone, we can leave solution pits in place to continue their slow geologic growth.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT | Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT'] | Time Stamp: 1642022078

This needed and exhausting work helped further Bryce Canyon National Park's goal of reducing fuels within the park. This is/was a group effort that involved other volunteer crews, National Park Service personnel, and conservation crews throughout 2021.<\br>.<\br>A *hard* job well done by all 👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼<\br>.<\br>Bryce Canyon National Park News Release: Bryce Canyon To Burn Hand Piles Next Week<\br>.<\br>...This project began in 2020, using mechanical methods such as chainsaws to thin downed and crowded trees. The debris was then placed into hand piles to dry and later burn once snow and other weather conditions were favorable for visitor and firefighter safety.<\br>.<\br>Prescribed fires like these reduce hazardous fuel build-up. This not only helps to maintain fire's natural role in this ecosystem, but protects sensitive cultural and natural resources within the park. Similar work in the Rainbow Point area was crucial to wildland fire crews’ ability to safely manage the Riggs and Lonely fires. Post_ID: 2749091059255795551 | Post_Code: CYmu8DKJN9f | Likes: 30 | Caption: My thoughts on access<\br><\br>My buddy @aidan.pinsk recently posted on his account with some thoughts about access, and it got me inspired to make a post that I think is a bit overdue for me.<\br><\br>Access is a huge part in the developing world of Outdoor Rec. The OR world is predominantly white, strong men. Women have not been shown in the OAE world, but many organizations like NOLS and Outward Bound are trying to improve on that. <\br><\br>I think we need to be more inclusive with other minority groups like BIPOC, AAPI, and LGBTQ. Adding them into sports that they may not be able to afford or make them feel comfortable in a climbing gym where they're the minority. I have personally experienced this while working at my local climbing gym. I've seen men really enjoy the sport and ask questions on how they can get stronger but I have also seen women who are new to the sport not really enjoy it because they feel weak or not invited. Some have approached me after they try it out, some have dropped little hints while I am walking around checking in on guests, some even feel uncertainty or uncomfortable while i'm just doing a basic orientation on the facility. When people ask about getting their own gear, I always tell them that it's going to cost you $250+ for a full set of gear, and that tends to draw people away, especially those of lower income. But I have to be honest as a salesperson and staff member. <\br><\br>Also commenting on what Aidan spoke about, do research on the lands you live on, the lands you recreate on, look at the historical impact they may have and protect those lands. There's so many access battles that are going on that are unheard of. We just recently got back Bears Ears, but are now in a battle for The Grand Tetons. Even just tiny things like using boars hair brushes to brush off rock holds or like Aidan mentioned, using rosin-less chalk. LNT (Leave No Trace) is a principle that needs to be publicized and standardized across the world. Pack it in, pack it out. Leave the area you were recreating at cleaner than it was when you got there. If you see trash that isn't yours, take it with you and throw it away. <\br><\br>Continued in comments ⬇️<\br><\br>#lnt #leavenotrace #access | Tags: ['#lnt', '#leavenotrace', '#access'] | Time Stamp: 1641937213

Post_ID: 2748289542971688989 | Post_Code: CYj4sc8v4gd | Likes: 134 | Caption: Let’s talk PERMITS…<\br><\br>If you’re a photographer planning a shoot or a couple planning a wedding, this is for you. So be sure to SAVE this post for future reference.<\br><\br>Permitting applies for most state and national parks. Permitting protects public lands, helps to control traffic, and can provide funding. Permitting can be a hassle at times, but they are well worth having. Why? Because it’s the law. Even if you’re doing a simple session, your photographer may need a permit. And if you’re planning a wedding ceremony in a park, it’s almost guaranteed. <\br><\br>To find information about permitting, go directly to the website of whichever state or national park you’re interested in. They almost always have permitting information readily available. If not, just call or email. Parks try their best to get back to you because they want you to have the permit as much as you want it. <\br><\br>Generally an application is required and needs to be submitted by a certain deadline. For most parks it’s 30 days, but every park is different. <\br><\br>If you choose not to get a permit, there can be serious repercussions. A photographer can lose the ability to acquire a permit with future state and national parks, which can  greatly harm their business. If caught without one, you can suffer major fines and whatever event or shoot is going on, can be immediately terminated — which would be terrible on a wedding day and very awkward on a shoot. <\br><\br>Long story short, get your permits in order before any major event or shoot! It benefits both yourself and the park you love. Most of all, it keeps these incredible public lands that we love available for decades to come!<\br>•<\br>•<\br>•<\br>#protectpubliclands #leavenotrace #lnt #respectnature #washingtonelopementphotographer #washingtonelopement #washingtonphotographer #washingtonphotography #seattleelopementphotographer #seattleelopement #pnwelopementphotographer #pnwelopement #pnwphotographer #elopementguide #elopementinspiration #nationalparkwedding #nationalparkelopement #annigrahameffects #lumineeffects | Tags: ['#protectpubliclands', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#respectnature', '#washingtonelopementphotographer', '#washingtonelopement', '#washingtonphotographer', '#washingtonphotography', '#seattleelopementphotographer', '#seattleelopement', '#pnwelopementphotographer', '#pnwelopement', '#pnwphotographer', '#elopementguide', '#elopementinspiration', '#nationalparkwedding', '#nationalparkelopement', '#annigrahameffects', '#lumineeffects'] | Time Stamp: 1641841665

You can follow where the animals have been, where the trees provide protection, and most of all you can see the footsteps of the last travelers. It’s comforting in a way! It’s welcoming to see. I try hard to protect what I know is so special! And I encourage others to do the same! The next time you see someone not treating the precious land around us the way it deserves…KINDLY speak up. Stick up for our lovely little mountains. #LNT 💛🏔<\br><\br>#hike #hiking #therootednomad #mountain #mountains #NH #newhampshire #dakine #snow #winter #sunset #turtlefur #salomon #puffer #puffyjacket #buff #rei #lahouts #kahtoola #darntoughsocks #thenorthface #petzle #blackdiamond #trees #cliff #osprey #patagonia #nalgene #thermarest | Tags: ['#LNT', '#hike', '#hiking', '#therootednomad', '#mountain', '#mountains', '#NH', '#newhampshire', '#dakine', '#snow', '#winter', '#sunset', '#turtlefur', '#salomon', '#puffer', '#puffyjacket', '#buff', '#rei', '#lahouts', '#kahtoola', '#darntoughsocks', '#thenorthface', '#petzle', '#blackdiamond', '#trees', '#cliff', '#osprey', '#patagonia', '#nalgene', '#thermarest'] | Time Stamp: 1641787225

Post_ID: 2747330247747283957 | Post_Code: CYgek3pqav1 | Likes: 7 | Caption: ✨✨✨ He agotado el espacio del anterior... ✨✨✨<\br>Prosigo!<\br><\br>Estábamos con el spray hidroalcoholico pandémico:<\br>En un botecito de spray de tamaño bolso, echa aprox 2/3 de alcohol, unas 10 gotas de aceites esenciales (mono esencias, o tu mezcla favorita), y mi ingrediente secreto, un par de gotas de aloe vera en gel.  Resto, agua.  La queja más habitual es que el gel hidroalcoholico reseca las manos.  Con este spray casero se quedan las manos suavitas, desinfectadas, y a la vez haces aromaterapia.  Todas las veces al día que sea necesario. <\br><\br>Ambientador casero:<\br>Sabes la de químicos nocivos que llevan los ambientadores comerciales? <\br>Te recomiendo que te hagas tu ambientador casero, con tus aceites esenciales favoritos.  Además, puedes rociar los en sábanas, en la almohada antes de dormir si haces una mezcla para el insomnio, o en la ropa limpia, o en tu bufanda favorita, antes de salir de casa.... <\br>Mi receta:  un tercio del bote, rellenado con alcohol, otro tercio con agua, y otro tercio con hidrolato (de Rosas, de lavanda, de lo que tu quieras). Si no quieres o no tienes hidrolato, pues dos tercios de agua y ya está.  Sin complicaciones.  Y añade tus gotitas favoritas. <\br><\br>Consejos varios:<\br>1. Hazte con una "aromateca" poco a poco.  Tu Estado de ánimo, tus necesidades y tus gustos van cambiando.  Te aconsejo que tengas esencias para elegir. <\br>2. Invierte en esencias de calidad.  Hay diferencia de precio, sí, pero la diferencia en calidad es abismal. <\br>Hay "aceites esenciales", y aceites a los que añaden aromatizantes para que huelan bien.  Recurre a marcas de confianza. <\br>3. Cúrratelo! Hay cientos de páginas donde explican usos, cualidades y aplicaciones de toooodos los aceites esenciales del mercado.  Busca los que quieres utilizar, elige tus aromas favoritos entre los que tengan propiedades deseables para ti y para los tuyos. <\br>4. Mezcla.  Prueba.  Encuentra tus favoritos.  Aprovecha esta maravillosa herramienta que puede ayudarte y ayudar a otros. <\br><\br>En otro post explicaré los usos de los aceites esenciales para hacer limpieza energética de espacios y superficies. <\br><\br>#aromaterapia #aceitesesenciales #trabajosenergeticos #limpiatucasa #LNT #limpiezaenergetica | Tags: ['#aromaterapia', '#aceitesesenciales', '#trabajosenergeticos', '#limpiatucasa', '#LNT', '#limpiezaenergetica'] | Time Stamp: 1641727308

When we get to the paved road that takes us into the next town, we still haven't seen Bison. I try and figure out what he may have done while we eat lunch. Post_ID: 2746746046296733037 | Post_Code: CYeZvnpubVt | Likes: 35 | Caption: When we lead trips, we practice the seven Leave No Trace (LNT) principles. These principles are a set of guidelines that are meant to minimize human impact for anyone visiting the outdoors: <\br><\br>1. Plan ahead and prepare<\br>2. Travel and camp on durable surfaces<\br>3. Dispose of waste properly<\br>4. Leave what you find<\br>5. Minimize campfire impacts<\br>6. Respect wildlife<\br>7. Be considerate of other visitors <\br><\br>While these were originally developed for exploration of the backcountry, they are equally applicable in frontcountry locations or anywhere outside! By following these rules, you are doing your part to help maintain healthy ecosystems for plants and animals to thrive in 🌎<\br><\br>Want more information about Leave No Trace? Check out their website here: https://lnt.org/<\br><\br>📸: Savannah McCauley<\br><\br>📍 Native Lands - Apsaalooké (Crow), Eastern Shoshone, Tséstho’e (Cheyenne)<\br><\br>Image Description: [A group of people smile as they set up camp in Grand Teton National Park. Post_ID: 2746137580335471893 | Post_Code: CYcPZRkPx0V | Likes: 31 | Caption: RADICAL RESPONSIBILITY FOR RADICAL FREEDOM<\br>Do you want to be free? Freedom has been one of my main goals, if not the main one, for my whole life. Since I was a child, I've never liked to be told what to do. As a teenager, I thought that freedom entailed to rebel against authority, to party and get wasted. This went on into adulthood, when travelling was added to partying in an attempt to break free from a routine that felt boring and unmotivating. And I was lucky enough to be economically supported by my family while I studied in university for many years, in different countries. All my material needs were covered, I could organize my days as I pleased (other than studying), but was I free? I would regularly feel trapped in a life that felt wrong, but I didn't know what to do, so I just distracted and numbed myself and kept going to the next degree, the next job, the next relationship, the next trip, the next party. All this has only changed THANKS TO MY MENTAL HEALTH PROBLEMS. Yes, I say THANKS because any health issues, especially mental ones, are just a message, an indicator that something is wrong with us and we need to change our approach to life. Only when shit got real for me, when I started having daily anxiety, crying fits and suicidal thoughts I had the motivation to REALLY search for answers, to really look into the bottom of my heart and soul, to really take my health into my own hands. How? By OWNING MY PROBLEMS. Every single one. By taking radical responsibility for everything that was not working in my life, and committing to doing something about each single thing I didn't like. By stopping looking for someone to blame, and start finding something to do to fix the problem. Because it doesn't matter whose fault your issues are (disclaimer: our problems are most often of our own creation), what matters is that the only person that can do something to solve them and transform your life is ultimately YOU. And if you don't do anything and just keep going on auto-pilot, know that your subconscious (often limiting) beliefs acquired from your family, school and society since childhood are the ones running your life. So what are you gonna do about that? | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1641585131

Post_ID: 2745616306806056086 | Post_Code: CYaY3vwseSW | Likes: 376 | Caption: ↟ Sharing Respect ↟<\br>↟<\br>I’m deeply concerned about current trends wherein some choose to vandalize or otherwise destroy public lands, national parks, and/or sacred Native American spaces. This week’s episode in @bigbendnps is no exception. Why do some among us behave so irresponsibly?<\br>↟<\br>One theory I’m willing to test states that our rash of recent infractions are simply due to the percentages. Since COVID forced so many indoors for so long, a higher number of people than before recreate outdoors upon emergence from lock-down. These large numbers also translate into a higher number (but equal %) of yo-yos spending time in campgrounds, national parks, and on hiking trails. More people, more dupewads. Thankfully, I actually noticed far fewer people on our local trails in 2021 than in 2020, so if this percentage play really does correlate with these increases in irresponsible behavior, then I’m satisfied that as this crazy world eventually returns to “normal,” the crowds and number of bozos will eventually diminish.<\br>↟<\br>Another theory I have is that ubiquitous cameras and closed-network sharing are to blame. While it can be easy to throw rocks at online social media as the root of modern evil, I think the problem is more elegant than that. The fact is, we simply don’t see that many idiots bragging online about their heinous acts of destruction. If and when the morons do take to social media for their public flaunting, such acts often get quickly shamed, rather than celebrated. Nevertheless, because every pocket now carries a camera, those troubled enough to vandalize also have the effortless ability to record their diabolical deeds; not for the world to see and celebrate, but merely to share with their own select few, via text messaging or other closed channels.<\br>↟<\br>So what are we to do?<\br>↟<\br>📸: May 2021<\br>↟<\br>↟<\br>↟<\br>↟<\br>↟<\br>#hiking #hikingadventures #hikeutah #hiketheparks #getoutside #desert #optoutside #americasbestidea #canyonlandsnationalpark #canyonlandsnps #desertsunrise #goldenhour #backpacking #campingculture #trailetiquette #protectthewild #packitinpackitout #outdoorlife #adventureresponsibly #naturefirst #leaveitbetter #nationalparks #sidewiththeoutside #lnt #leavenotrace | Tags: ['#hiking', '#hikingadventures', '#hikeutah', '#hiketheparks', '#getoutside', '#desert', '#optoutside', '#americasbestidea', '#canyonlandsnationalpark', '#canyonlandsnps', '#desertsunrise', '#goldenhour', '#backpacking', '#campingculture', '#trailetiquette', '#protectthewild', '#packitinpackitout', '#outdoorlife', '#adventureresponsibly', '#naturefirst', '#leaveitbetter', '#nationalparks', '#sidewiththeoutside', '#lnt', '#leavenotrace'] | Time Stamp: 1641522991

Post_ID: 2745465744134583164 | Post_Code: CYZ2oxWJTN8 | Likes: 21 | Caption: No Deje Rastro <\br><\br>En esta época me ha tocado caminar por el borde del Río Ñuble y es !!😤💣🥊🤦🏽‍♀️‼️☢️ ver la cantidad de basura dejada por personas que van a pasar un rato o a acampar. <\br><\br>Es una muy mala costumbre dejar basura, no ser capaz de llevarte lo que trajiste. <\br>Para poder tener un mundo más limpio debemos, por ahora, hacer el trabajo de otros y llevarnos la basura que ellos dejan (Debemos educar, pero es lento el proceso) así que es una opción que ya muchos practican 👏🏼👏🏼.<\br><\br>PRINCIPIO 3 : Disponga adecuadamente de los desechos : si las personas están dejando esa basura muy fefinitivamente no están desechando adecuadamente su “número 2” (caca, heces, materia fecal, excremento 💩).<\br>No importa el nombre que le des, es muy desagradable saber que donde han estado personas pasando un rato, te vas a encontrar sus recuerdos...<\br><\br>Todos los que salen a la naturaleza, deberían saber que hacer a la hora de las necesidades básicas: no es difícil, solo es un poco más de esfuerzo:<\br>1- caminar lejos del lugar del campamento, lejos del agua fresca (ríos y arroyos), buscar un lugar donde sea menos probable que otros puedan acampar o transitar.<\br>2- hacer un hoyo de Gato (usar una pala), este deberá ser de unos 20 cm. de profundidad.<\br>3- luego de hacer la “diligencia” podrás dejar en el hoyo algún elemento usado para limpieza como hojas, palos, piedras. Pero NO el papel higiénico, este deberá ser guardado en una bolsita para ser depositado en la basura al retornar a la ciudad. <\br>4- luego tapar el hoyo tratando de no contaminar tu pala y dejar el lugar con el menor impacto visual de que alguien estuvo ahí.<\br><\br>Quieres saber más sobre<\br>No Deje Rastro y cómo estar en la naturaleza sin dañarla?<\br>Escríbenos y podemos dictar un curso para ti!!<\br><\br>... Qué hacemos con la pasta de dientes? 🥊Bonus points <\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>.<\br><\br>#nodejerastro #nodejerastro🇨🇱🍃💚 #lnt #leavenotrace #ndr #naturaleza #basuracero #basurachallenge #basura #sinbasura #rioslimpios #playaslimpias #llevatubasura #campamento #acampar #chilesinbasura #nature | Tags: ['#nodejerastro', '#nodejerastro🇨🇱🍃💚', '#lnt', '#leavenotrace', '#ndr', '#naturaleza', '#basuracero', '#basurachallenge', '#basura', '#sinbasura', '#rioslimpios', '#playaslimpias', '#llevatubasura', '#campamento', '#acampar', '#chilesinbasura', '#nature'] | Time Stamp: 1641505042

A number of hikers arrive, so to improve our chances of getting a ride all of the men move to a ditch out of site (women tend to have a better chance of someone stopping, so the trick is to wait until someone stops, then ask if they have room for more). Even with four women throwing their thumbs out we didn't have any luck. So I decided that a hitch will come if I'm doing something that would be inconvenient for me if a car were to stop. Check out the winter edition of the #RecreateResponsibly guidelines for tips on safe winter recreation:&nbsp; www.recreateresponsibly.org/winter<\br><\br>#RecreateResponsibly Winter Edition Guidelines:&nbsp;<\br><\br> * Know Before You Go - Some areas are seasonally closed or have limited hours, and many places become dangerous with winter weather. Research your destination, weather, and road conditions prior to your trip.&nbsp; <\br> * Plan and Prepare&nbsp;- Know your limits and your gear. Pack extra layers, waterproof clothing, and safety equipment or beacons for the backcountry. Have a Plan B in case you can’t access your destination.&nbsp; <\br> * Build an Inclusive Outdoors - Everyone deserves to experience a winter wonderland. Be an active part of making the outdoors safe, accessible, and welcoming for all identities and abilities.&nbsp; <\br> * Respect Others - From mountain tops to shores to prairies, parking can be in short supply in the winter. Park only in safe and legal spaces. Learn to Ski Kind or Tread Lightly when skiing, riding, or traversing off-road.&nbsp;&nbsp; <\br> * Leave No Trace - Respect the land, water, wildlife, and Indigenous communities. Follow the Leave No Trace Winter Use Principles.&nbsp; <\br> * Make it Better - Keep our winter playgrounds clean. Pack out any human or pet waste. Consider your responsibility to take action to protect our climate--today’s snow is tomorrow’s water. | Tags: ['#RecreateResponsibly', '#RecreateResponsibly'] | Time Stamp: 1641414155

Es un miedo, terror fuerte e irracional donde dificulta el desarrollo de la vida diaria. El pánico que algunas personas sienten bloquea y limita a quien las sufre. Si no se le pone remedio se puede convertir en una&nbsp; enfermedad.<\br><\br>Se tienen síntomas como dificultad al respirar, dolores de cabeza, aceleración de la frecuencia cardíaca, sudoración…lo que se desencadena es un miedo que no se puede controlar.<\br><\br>Lo más recomendable para superar una fobia es a través de un profesional de la salud. Este le dirá el tipo de terapia que es la más adecuada y los pasos a seguir. Así le identificará que la causa o cual es el motivo por lo que se genera dicha fobia para normalizar los síntomas que la producen.<\br><\br>También hay alternativas a la medicina tradicional como son la SANACIÓN ENERGÉTICA Y CUÁNTICA DE LA LNT®. Este método es novedoso y ofrece resultados excelentes. Concretamente, la medicina cuántica se caracteriza por aplicar una serie de técnicas de sanación en las que hay una relación directa entre las emociones, los pensamientos y las células<\br><\br>Lo que se pretende es encontrar las debilidades que puedan generar el malestar físico o bloqueo emocional que impida un equilibrio personal. <\br><\br>Este tipo de terapia sanadora utiliza los avances de la física cuántica. En cada terapia,  buscamos el Conflicto Programante, pero ¿por qué? Para encontrar y liberar este resentir en el Conflicto Programante.<\br><\br>El hecho de saber de manera precisa y concreta ayudar a la persona a liberar el resentir es el acto de sanación más poderoso en terapia de descodificación. En todo este arte, es en el que se basa la Descodificación.<\br> <\br>En este taller de 4h  vamos a repasar los diferentes resentires, vamos a definir bien la Biodiana y hacer prácticas para dominar este arte de la sanación que es la liberación del resentir.<\br><\br>👨‍🏫 Impartido por Jean Guillaume Salles<\br><\br>📅 Fecha y horario: 19 de enero de 19h a 23h<\br><\br>💵 Precio:  60€ hasta el 5 de enero / 70€ desde el día 6 hasta el día del curso.<\br><\br>Puedes comprar el curso en https://www.biodecodage.es/cursos<\br><\br>#biodècodage #christianfleche #bioemoción #medicinaalternativa #bioneuroemoción #DescodificaciónBiológica #BiodécodagePráctica #salud #enfermedad #emociones #descodificación #conciencia #LeyesBiológicas #síntomas #bienestar #desarrollopersonal #transgeneracional #desprogramación #bioshock #constelacionesfamiliares #couch #creencias #psicólogos #psicoanalistas #terapiacraneosacral #osteopatia #pnl #psicogenalogía #kinesiologia #LNT <\br>- | Tags: ['#biodècodage', '#christianfleche', '#bioemoción', '#medicinaalternativa', '#bioneuroemoción', '#DescodificaciónBiológica', '#BiodécodagePráctica', '#salud', '#enfermedad', '#emociones', '#descodificación', '#conciencia', '#LeyesBiológicas', '#síntomas', '#bienestar', '#desarrollopersonal', '#transgeneracional', '#desprogramación', '#bioshock', '#constelacionesfamiliares', '#couch', '#creencias', '#psicólogos', '#psicoanalistas', '#terapiacraneosacral', '#osteopatia', '#pnl', '#psicogenalogía', '#kinesiologia', '#LNT'] | Time Stamp: 1641312495

Post_ID: 2743319382263311804 | Post_Code: CYSOnGFP628 | Likes: 32 | Caption: Happy Monday! We're kicking off 2022 by sharing some of the kinds of work Wilderness Volunteers does on our stewardship projects.<\br>.<\br>This November, our 2021 Leader Trainees spent the week in the San Rafael Swell in east-central Utah. Their challenge: removing the invasive tamarisk from the wash, to reinforce annual removal efforts. <\br>.<\br>What is tamarisk you ask? Tamarisk is an invasive shrub or small tree that is found across the American West. Also known as salt cedar, Tamarisk is a thirsty plant with a high evapotranspiration rate, taking lots of water and releasing it into the air. It competes with native plants and can displace riparian habitats. This invasive species can and does alter habitat quality for some wildlife, water use by floodplain vegetation, and the frequency and intensity of wildfires.<\br>.<\br>Our crew of leader trainees diligently worked in the North Fork Coal Wash with a thoughtful strategy to attack sections of the wash, coordinating the cutting, flagging, and moving on so a finishing spray could be applied no later than 10 minutes after the cut. Our agency partners assisted in big tamarisk cutting jobs with chainsaw support and managed all aspects of spraying.<\br>.<\br>This project was an excellent practice in communication, coordination, patience, and we are very thankful and proud of our leader trainee crew! Y'all rose to the challenge, worked cohesively with each other, and removed a lot of cumbersome, intertwined tamarisk. We thank you for your hard work, we thank the BLM folks at the Price Field Office, and we look forward to heading back in 2023 to see how our efforts held up. <\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#wildernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #wv2021SanRafaelSwell #stewardship #conservation #SanRafaelSwell #SanRafaelSwellRecreationArea #theswell #northforkcoalwash #bureauoflandmanagement #blm #tamariskremoval #tamarisk #saltcedar #invasive #utah #leavenotrace #lnt #clipping #cutting #slipperarch #thedrips #swaseysarch #volunteer #hiking  #SidsMountainWildernessStudyArea #sidsmountain #swamping #sandstonecanyon #naturalarches | Tags: ['#wildernessvolunteers', '#givingsomethingback', '#wv2021SanRafaelSwell', '#stewardship', '#conservation', '#SanRafaelSwell', '#SanRafaelSwellRecreationArea', '#theswell', '#northforkcoalwash', '#bureauoflandmanagement', '#blm', '#tamariskremoval', '#tamarisk', '#saltcedar', '#invasive', '#utah', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#clipping', '#cutting', '#slipperarch', '#thedrips', '#swaseysarch', '#volunteer', '#hiking', '#SidsMountainWildernessStudyArea', '#sidsmountain', '#swamping', '#sandstonecanyon', '#naturalarches'] | Time Stamp: 1641249176

"You gotta settle down, Irene", a little voice inside my head would say, "You are an adult now, get serious already". Or, as a former boyfriend pointed out to me: "You can't live like an exchange student forever". Can't I? The truth is I don't know if I have ever felt truly at home anywhere I have lived: Spain, Italy, France, Belgium. I adapt easily, for sure. But home? That is a big word. In February 2020 I finally graduated from my doctorate and gave myself permission to travel the world, looking for a place worth of that title. Perfect timing, right? Fast-forward a pandemic and a burnout later, I can finally set off, taking my first trips within Europe to stay safe. I've had two professional burnouts in my 31 years of life, the first one was cured mostly with travel, together with psychotherapy. But surprise surprise, this second time I had gone beyond what my nervous system could sustain and no matter how many different therapies I was doing it never seemed to be enough. I spent 2021 trying all therapy forms I could find: yoga therapy, ayurveda, counselling, family constellations, energy healing, osteopathy, hypnosis, LNT... The solution? Learning how to truly put it all together in a holistic body-mind-spirit approach, to nourish and calm my nervous system, but also facing my deepest trauma and psychological patterns that had got me sick in first place. It's been hard work, but thanks to that I can now say that I feel at home with myself, wherever I go. And I know that soon, as I keep travelling, I will find a place where I will truly feel like staying. In the meantime, however, I am ok with not knowing, and just enjoying the ride. Es el color más tradicional del ojo turco.<\br>*El&nbsp;azul claro&nbsp;se vincula con el color del cielo; simboliza la verdad y ofrece directa protección frente al mal de ojo.<\br>*El&nbsp;rojo, relacionado con la sangre y el amor, es el color de la energía, el poder y la determinación, así como de la pasión y el deseo.<\br>*El&nbsp;amarillo, color del sol, simboliza la fuerza y la vitalidad; es el color de la salud y el vigor físico.<\br>*El&nbsp;verde&nbsp;es el color de la naturaleza; simboliza la esperanza y el crecimiento personal.<\br>*El&nbsp;blanco&nbsp;se asocia a la luz; simboliza la bondad, la inocencia; es el color de la perfección, que limpia y purifica energías negativas y las transforma en positivas.<\br>*El&nbsp;violeta&nbsp;es el color de la nobleza; simboliza el poder y la ambición y se asocia, también, a cualidades como la sabiduría, la dignidad, la independencia, la creatividad, el misterio y la magia.<\br><\br>Cada uno tiene el suyo...<\br><\br>Espero haberte movilizado como yo con este post... que tengas buen dia! Post_ID: 2740225649153067025 | Post_Code: CYHPLWmLsgR | Likes: 26 | Caption: Day 85 (Fri 7/9): Into Steamboat Springs<\br><\br>Bison and I wake up, pack up, and PDF comes down the way feeling much better than yesterday. It's a loooooooooooong road walk to get to the hitching point. We get picked up by @diggerdogger who has the same bad taste in music as me and also gave us croutons from a giant box of croutons he had. We get dropped off at a KFC/Taco Bell and eat two meals each. We then hip on a bus and head into town. We walk around a bit then meet up with @heyspamcake and @lianavit. The bartender of the place we are at offers us her place to stay for the evening, which is great because all of the hotel rooms are booked in town for the rodeo and hot air balloon festival. PDF attempts to yogi us into the rodeo, but the folks at the ticket counter just let us go in anyways (the rodeo is halfway over when we get there). A bunch of people at the rodea are interested in what we're doing. We probably had five separate groups talk to us. We then hangout with our bartender Georgie at her place before sleeping in her side yard. Did I mention Bison and I have decided we're not going to sleep indoors the entire month of July? Y no es para menos, este año ha sido el mas transformador de toda mi vida. <\br>Me he enfrentado al miedo tantas veces que ahora ya no le tengo miedo al miedo. El miedo es guay, porque si lo atraviesas, si le miras a los ojos, si lo sientes lo mas que puedas, desaparece y cuando vuelve tu ya estas preparada para recibirlo con los brazos abiertos, porque sabes que después del miedo llega el regalo de recompensa. Eso que no creías posible, eso que jamás pensabas que sería para ti. <\br>Cuando te transformas te quedas sola, mueres en cierto modo porque no puedes volver a lo que eras antes, es un camino de no retorno. Hay personas que se apartan de tu vida, tu frecuencia energética cambia y ya no sintonizas con algunas personas. Hay un tiempo largo de soledad, porque solo asi puedes escuchar tu propia voz interna. No hay transformación sin soledad. No la hay. <\br>Cuando estoy abajo es porque me es difícil seguir en este mundo disfrazado, donde prácticamente todo el mundo lleva una máscara puesta, por miedo de que lo vean de verdad. La máscara de “madre”, “marido”, “jefe”, “ empleado”, etiquetas mil.
